3.5 Schema Considerations & Observations

(Merged from Phase 1 analysis)

1. Indexing Considerations

Some fields benefit from additional indexes not present by default:

Recommended indexes for performance:
- purchase.userId (for user subscription queries)
- purchase.status (for status filtering)
- purchase.currentPeriodEnd (for grace period queries)
- purchase.referralCode (for affiliate lookups)
- user.referredBy (for referral analysis)
- user.discordId (for Discord integration)
- user.lastLoginAt (for active user queries)
- user.deletedAt (for soft-delete filtering)

Index syntax example:
```prisma
@@index([userId, status])  // Composite index
@@index([referralCode])    // Single field index
```

2. Nullable Fields & Data Integrity

Certain foreign keys are nullable by design, allowing unusual states:

Purchase Model:
- userId and organizationId both nullable
- Design allows: user purchases OR organization purchases
- Lifepreneur use: userId always set, organizationId always null
- Implication: Queries must handle null cases

Status Field:
- Purchase.status is String? (nullable)
- Can be null on initial creation
- Should always have value after webhook processing
- Queries must handle null status edge case

3. Consistency Across Models

Inconsistent naming conventions across models:

Field Name Patterns:
- Supastarter defaults: camelCase (emailVerified, createdAt)
- Database mapping: snake_case with @map (email_verified, created_at)
- Some models inconsistent within themselves

Example Inconsistency:
```prisma
model User {
  emailVerified Boolean        // No @map
  onboardingComplete Boolean @default(false)  // No @map
  paymentsCustomerId String?  // No @map
  
  // Extended fields use @map:
  discordId String? @map("discord_id")
  referredBy String? @map("referred_by")
}
```

Timestamp Naming:
- createdAt / updatedAt (most models)
- created_at / updated_at (some models with @map)
- Inconsistent across different tables

Foreign Key Naming:
- userId (User relation)
- user_id (with @map in some models)
- Mixed usage across schema

4. Migration Order Sensitivity

The extended models introduce dependencies requiring careful ordering:

Dependency Chain:
1. User model extensions (must come first)
2. Purchase model extensions (depends on User)
3. New models (ContentVideo, Affiliate, etc.)
4. Relations and foreign keys
5. Indexes for performance

Circular Dependency Risk:
- User → Affiliate (one-to-one)
- Affiliate → User (reverse relation)
- Must define both sides correctly

Migration Strategy:
- Extend existing tables before adding new tables
- Add fields before adding relations
- Add indexes after data structure is stable
- Test migrations on development database first

5. Type Safety Issues

Several type safety concerns identified:

String? vs Nullable Types:
- Purchase.status is String? (no compile-time safety)
- Should ideally be enum but Stripe sends various values
- Requires runtime validation

Enum vs String:
- PurchaseType uses proper enum (SUBSCRIPTION | ONE_TIME) ✓
- Purchase.status uses String? (not type-safe) ✗
- Cancellation reasons could use enum ✗

JSON Fields:
- metadata fields use Json type
- No type safety for JSON content
- Requires manual parsing and validation

6. Data Integrity Patterns

Observed patterns for maintaining data integrity:

Cascade Deletes:
- User deletion cascades to: Sessions, Accounts, Purchases, etc.
- Prevents orphaned records
- Correctly implemented via onDelete: Cascade

Unique Constraints:
- User.email @unique
- User.username @unique
- Purchase.subscriptionId @unique
- Prevents duplicate critical data

Default Values:
- Boolean fields often have @default(false)
- Timestamps use @default(now())
- Counters use @default(0)
- Ensures consistent initial state

