9.2 Stripe Event Model - Detailed

The following Stripe events influence subscription state:

CURRENTLY HANDLED (packages/payments/provider/stripe/index.ts):

✅ checkout.session.completed
   - Creates ONE_TIME Purchase
   - Sets customerId on entity
   - Fires on: One-time product purchases

✅ customer.subscription.created  
   - Creates SUBSCRIPTION Purchase
   - Sets initial status from Stripe
   - Links to user via metadata.user_id
   - Sets subscriptionId for future updates

✅ customer.subscription.updated
   - Updates Purchase.status
   - Updates Purchase.productId (if plan changed)
   - Requires existing Purchase lookup by subscriptionId
   - Fires on: Plan changes, status changes, cancellations

✅ customer.subscription.deleted
   - Deletes Purchase record entirely via deletePurchaseBySubscriptionId()
   - ⚠️ No soft-delete, immediate removal from database
   - Fires on: Subscription end, immediate cancellation

NOT HANDLED (Need to Add):

❌ invoice.payment_failed
   - Should trigger grace_period status
   - Should increment paymentFailureCount on User
   - Should send grace period warning email
   - Should log EmailLog entry

❌ invoice.paid
   - Should send payment confirmation email
   - Should reset payment failure counters
   - Should update lastPaymentDate
   - Should log successful payment

❌ invoice.upcoming
   - Could send renewal reminder email
   - Fires 7 days before renewal (configurable)

❌ charge.refunded
   - Should log refund event
   - May need to adjust subscription status
   - Should trigger admin notification

⚠️ Event Handling Characteristics:

- Unhandled events return 200 status (logged but ignored)
- No idempotency checks (Stripe may retry)
- No event ordering guarantees
- Webhook secret validation is enforced
- Errors return 400 with message

The admin system depends on correct interpretation of:

period_end - For currentPeriodEnd field

status - For Purchase.status updates

cancellation flags - For cancelAtPeriodEnd tracking

payment failure indicators - For grace period logic

metadata fields - For user/organization attribution

9.3 Handling Grace Periods

Grace periods represent a temporary buffer after payment failure during which:

The user maintains full or limited access

System tracks failure counts

Extended metadata fields update:

Fields involved:

paymentFailureCount

gracePeriodUsedCount

lastPaymentFailureDate

Grace periods help prevent immediate churn while billing issues resolve.

9.4 Edge Cases & Recovery

Merged from Phase 5’s detailed findings, several edge-case scenarios exist:

1. Payment Method Issues

expired cards

insufficient funds

missing default payment methods

2. Invoice/Subscription Desync

Events may occur in a different order than expected or be delayed.

3. Duplicate Events

Stripe sends retries; idempotency must be logically ensured.

4. Out-of-Order Webhook Delivery

Subscriptions may temporarily enter incorrect intermediate states until later reconciliation.

5. Manual Cancellation from Dashboard

Admin or user cancellations trigger different states and metadata patterns.

6. Coupon Conflicts

Some coupon states interact unpredictably with extensions or proration.

7. Failures to Update Email Notifications

EmailLog should eventually store all outgoing attempts and capture failures.

These behaviors are described here conceptually, without directives.

